<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-975-238  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 975 238.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 18 1989 n279 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC: telcos violated limits on earnings. (10 Bell operatingcompanies sued by ATandamp;T and MCI Communications Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killette, Kathleen.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>THE FCC has ruled that 10 Bell operating companies have violatedfederal limits on earnings by overcharging long-distance carriersfor some access services.andP;  ATandamp;T and MCI Communications Corp mayrecover as much as $15 million in damages if the ruling is upheld.andO;The two carriers filed complaints in 1987 charging that the Bellcompanies earned more than the rate of return the FCC prescribedand that their interstate access rates were unreasonable under theCommunications Act of 1934.andP;  Officials of the companies named inthe complaints conceded that their earnings were excessive in somecases, but argued that they did not earn too much overall.andP;  FCCChmn Alfred Sikes states that he sees the ruling as complementingthe agency's recent ban on 'strategically priced' tariffs.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (cases)MCI Communications Corp. (cases).andO;Ticker:    MCIC; T.andO;Topic:     Bell Regional Holding CompaniesGovernment RegulationLegal IssuesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionCommunications IndustryProfitCommunications Service Suppliers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>